<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-11-12T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-11-12T02:00:00-05:00" n="465" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d465">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">196.1/11–1245: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Meyer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-11-12T15:00:00+08:00">November 12,
                                1945—3 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received November 14—5:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>24. Your 17, November 5.<note n="18" xml:id="d465fn18">See footnote 3, <ref target="#pg_603">p. 603</ref>.</note> Jeep party returned to ship
                        with exception of Lieutenant Commander Oko who was slightly wounded and is
                        now in Marine Hospital at Chinwangtao. Written reports will be available in
                        a day or two. Sent to Shanghai; repeated to Department and Chungking.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Meyer</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>